>it's probably the dominant thing
Essentially this. When it happens, it's usually spun out of larger trends about seeing animals as physically imposing compared to humans and all that stuff about primal nature and so on. Of course, in reality things aren't quite like that, notably with canines themselves. Who are rarely so big as to measure up to people, much less that being the average. On the whole, humans have a habit of killing all the really big animals, either by out competing them or just straight up muderizing them out of existence.

It's probably a confirmation bias thing too. For male anthros on human females, they're still liable to be bigger than the humans, but they're also guys so it's expected. When trying to play the same roles but gender flipped, the female anthros end up bigger to keep that physical difference aspect, but now it becomes another oddity because bigger women is much rarer than the other way around.

Ok, I had to run to the shops, but I'm mostly done. I was going to just reference some particularly egregious examples, but there's just so much, so I tried fiddling with it in google docs. Here's the linkeroo, if you want to see it as the clean edited version, go to Tools -> Review suggested edits.
docs.google.com/document/d/1MDrBwPxqgynOkhu9k6HFhS2HF0cIdXCU6DRBi5yzH1U/edit?usp=sharing

First thing's first, pay attention to your spell checker. It'll at least catch all the simple spelling mistakes - of which there are a surprising amount of in this, such as compliations, ment, chuckels, pinneing, etc - and some of the better ones can find more complex grammar issues.

Secondly, I'd suggest making sure you're sticking to one specific style throughout an entire story. You're not what I'd call an 'experienced' writer, so switching from traditional greentext format into something more akin to standard prose halfway through isn't doing much to help you maintain a normalised and sane looking structure, which doesn't do much to help me proofread it, nor does it do much to help you grow as a writer. Tense and even perspective changes throughout the story - at one point you switched into third person and referred the the main character as 'Anon' rather than 'you', but then switched back a little while later. Given that, it's difficult to compare different segments of your story and judge what you're doing poorly and what you're doing well since there's no real baseline structure to judge it from.

I tried not changing too much, mostly just grammar errors, but there's a lot of really, really weird syntax in there that's not just related to the usual greentext oddities. I understand now why someone would think you're ESL. But, I guess that's the strength of the greentext style: you don't have to be Shakespear to convey an emotion and have it understood by some jack off on the other side of the world.
